The primary data sources are open-source files from GitHub and other platforms such as Discord.", "category": "Bounty", "timeline": {"status": "DRAFT"}, "supervisor": "yarotska.near", "description": "**About OpenQ**\\\\n\\\\nOpenQ is a developer relationship management platform that collects and analyzes developer data to track relevant developers and measure overall activity.\\\\n\\\\nThis process primarily involves downloading large amounts of open-source files based on requested projects added to our platform or using one of our features to find relevant projects. We then track based on configuration files whether the project is using near-related dev tools to ensure they are either deploying a project to Near or building Near-related dev tools. Through this method, we can determine which projects are relevant from individual developers and assess their activity levels.\\\\n\\\\nThis analysis can be conducted on a large scale to understand the overall community or on smaller scales, such as calculating the developer activity of hackathon participants or attendees of other events, educational programs, or grant programs.\\\\n\\\\nAll of these features are integrated into our platform, which the Near team will have access to for tracking various OKRs for future success. Additionally, they can create notes on teams or developers, providing a centralized repository for developer relations efforts that the Near team can access at any time.\\\\n\\\\n**Why**\\\\n\\\\nThere are multiple reasons why our platform is needed for the Near team:\\\\n\\\\n1) We aim to assist in analyzing the size of the Near developer community and determining which developer growth strategies are genuinely effective in increasing retention and attracting new individuals that deploy projects to Near.\\\\n\\\\n2) All the data we collect is exportable as .toml, which is the format used by Electric Capital to create their public developer community reports. By utilizing our platform, we not only aid in discovering developers who were not previously tracked but also identify new projects from developers whose repositories may be inactive.\\\\n\\\\n3) Ultimately, our goal is to ensure that proper OKRs can be analyzed and utilized to avoid wasting resources on growth efforts that yield little impact.\\\\n\\\\n**List of Services**\\\\n\\\\n- Expanding the Scope of KPIs\\\\nEnabling automatic detection of new users, returning users, and active users to add depth to KPIs.\\\\nFacilitating the calculation of user acquisition costs to determine the success of events.\\\\n\\\\n- Offering ROI Insights\\\\nMeasuring developer activity after events to determine outcomes and active user engagement.\\\\nComparing events and identifying the most beneficial ones to sponsor.\\\\n\\\\n- Automated Detection of Churn Ratios\\\\nAlerting you when developers remove your protocol from their GitHub configurations, enabling immediate engagement to understand their reasons (coming soon).\\\\nProviding insights into competitor communities to which developers may be moving.\\\\n\\\\n- Leveraging Algorithms for Prioritizing Actions\\\\nSummarizing all activities and automatically recommending actions for developer relations based on past experiences.\\\\nLearning from ROI data to identify the most effective actions for time investment, while continuously refining the approach.\\\\n\\\\n- Automated Overview of Developer Activities\\\\nIdentifying the most active developers and tracking their progress through comprehensive developer reports summarizing their GitHub code.\\\\nDetecting developers who become less active to re-engage and help them stay on track.\\\\n\\\\n**Integrations**\\\\n\\\\n- GitHub\\\\n- Discord (coming in the next 3 weeks)\\\\n\\\\nIf necessary, we can discuss new integrations in the future after this proposal and successful implementation.\\\\n\\\\n**Negotiated Terms with Near DevHub***\\\\n\\\\nOur pricing is based on the number of developers we track for your ecosystem. To kickstart this partnership, we are starting with a base package that allows tracking of 3000 developers. This offer is already discounted as we have been in discussions with Near since last year. It\\\\\\'s worth noting that our current pricing is higher, and this offer is part of our last deals with this pricing.\\\\nIf more developers need to be tracked, we will request further funding to finance our scraping operations. Additionally, we are offering 5 seats for the Near DevHub team and will support them in properly leveraging all our features.\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n", "linked_proposals": [], "receiver_account": "openq.near", "requested_sponsor": "events-committee.near", "proposal_body_version": "V0", "requested_sponsorship_usd_amount": "7200", "requested_sponsorship_paid_in_currency": "USDC"}, "labels": ["Other"]}
